<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-273  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 273.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 20 1990 v4 n30 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army cannot pay for CPU, board says. (the US General ServicesAdministration Board of Contract Appeals rules that the Army canuse but cannot pay for a Federal Data Corp CPU)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals(GSBCA) rules that the Army can use but cannot pay for anIBM-compatible CPU from Federal Data Corp following reinstatementof a protest by Vion Corp over the award.andP;  The US Court of Appealsfor the Federal Circuit ruled on Jul 25, 1990, that the GSBCAcould not dismiss a Vion protest simple because the company wasuncooperative during pretrial discovery.andP;  The court-orderedreinstatement of the Vion protest was to have caused the earliersuspension of the Army's delegation of procurement authority to goback into effect, but the Army awarded the contract to FederalData while the case was pending in the federal court, and systemshave already been installed in the Pentagon.andP;  The Army convincedthe board that the CPUs are critical to four major systemssupporting forecast of its personnel and equipment needs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Vion Corp. (cases)Federal Data Corp. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Government ContractsMilitaryCompetitive BiddingCourt CasesMicrocomputersHardware VendorsUnited States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppealsUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>